name: RENAL - PCT/LOH/DCT/CD
question1: DESCRIBE IN/OUT AT EACH PART OF KIDNEY. BASIC CELL, GLOMERULUS?
contents:
• Basic basal tubular cell layout
  • Tubular lumen - assorted mechanisms for selective reabsorption or secretion
  • Tubular cell
  • Apical (Lumen) side
  • Filtrate flow --> Assorted mechanisms for selective reabsorption or secretion.
  • Basal (Interstitial fluid lumen/plasma)
  • - passive conductance of K+, H20
  • - Na+/K+ ATPase maintains the low Na+ - this is the main active process in Na+ reabsorption
  • Glomerulus
  • Fluid composition :
  • Na+, HCO3,
  • glucose = same as plasma,
  • Protein = zero (Albumin Mol Wt 67,000)
  • Na+
  • Filtration 25000 mmol per day (40x as much Na+ is filtered as K+ but final urinary excretions are similar.
  • 99.5% Na+ reabsorbed.
  • The driving force behind the reabsorption of sodium and other ions is the Na+-K+-AT Pase pump, which acts at the Basilar (blood) wall of the tubular cell
  • It extrudes 3 Na+ into the interstitium in exchange for 2 K+ that are pumped into the cell.
  • Creates a Na+ gradient - between tubular lumen and cell such that sodium can diffuse passively into the cell from the lumen.


  • K+
  • Glomerular filtration : 720mmol per day
  • PCT : 65% passively reabsorbed
  • LoH: 25% reabsorbed actively in thick loop of Henle
  • DCT: Intercalated and principle cells in DCT determine final K+ excretion.
  • Excretion : 60mmol per day
  • normal baseline 90% reabsorbed.

  • stays horizontal at a concentration of 5-10mmol.l-1. unitl the DCT
  • K+ is secreted here along electrochemical gradients - which makes it unusual.
  • You should demonstrate that at low urinary flow rates, tubular K+ is higher at approximately 100 mmom.l-1 and so less K+ is secreted as the concentration gradient is reduced.


Where Na+ goes water follows - which provides an energy saving opportunity in the PCT

H20 follows --> Tubular Cl- increases --> Cl- reabsorbed down concentration gradient via paracellular route --> electrochemical gradient produced (+ve in tubule) --> drives lower energy Na+ absorption.
question2: DESCRIBE IN/OUT AT EACH PART OF KIDNEY. PCT - MAIN ROLE, REABSORPTION OF, COMPOSITION AT END?
contents2:
• Proximal Convoluted Tubule (PCT)
  • Main role: Conservation of the majority of the useful filtrate components


  • REABSORPTION OF Na+ IN PCT –(70%) 2 MAIN METHODS (H20 70% follows Na+)
  • Na+(IN)/H+(OUT) antiporter (apical/luminal side) --> H+ + HCO3- --> HCO3- + Na+(IN) co-transport (interstitial fluid/basal side)
  • Na+(IN)/Glucose(IN) symporter (apical/luminal side) --> Na+(IN) + K+ Active pump ATPase (interstitial fluid/basal side)
  • Reabsorption of HCO3 (99%)
  • Reabsorption of glucose (99%)
  • Fluid composition at end
  • Na+ - same as plasma
  • HCO3 - zero
  • Glucose - zero
question3: DESCRIBE IN/OUT AT EACH PART OF KIDNEY. LOH - MAIN ROLE, REABSORPTION OF?
contents3:
• Loop of Henle (LoH)
  • Main role :
  • producing HYPOtonic tubular fluid and HYPERtonic interstitial fluid (countercurrent)
  • some reabsorption of Na+, K+ and Cl-

  • Mechanisms:
  • selective permeabilities to ions and H20 in each limb,
  • combined with countercurrent multiplier (discuss active ion channel in ascending loop)
  • Descending into Medulla: H20 lost (AQP1) and Na+ retained (interstitial fluid more concentrated)
  • Ascending back into Interstitium: Ions lost and H20 retained
  • Fluid composition :
  • Massive extremes in osmolarity
  • starting tubular fluid : 300mOsm/l
  • Medulla interstitium : 1200mOsm/l
  • Returning tubular fluid : 100mOsm/l
  • Ion reabsorption:
  • K+ Na+(IN)/2Cl-(IN) co-transporter (apical/luminal side) --> Passive conductance K+ AND Na+(IN) + K+ Active pump ATPase (interstitial fluid/basal side)
  • Electrolytes pass from ascending LoH to descending limb of vasa recta; urea movement also contributes
  • Water passes from descending LoH to ascending limb of vasa recta
question4: DESCRIBE IN/OUT AT EACH PART OF KIDNEY. DCT - MAIN ROLE, REABSORPTION OF?
contents4:
• MAIN ROLE: DCT
  • Final regulation of extent of Na+, K+ and H+ excreted in urine
  • MECHANISM: specialized cells (2 types)
  • 1. Principal:
  • ENaC channels (antiporter) reabsorbs Na+ - secretes K+, primarily controlled by ALDOSTERONE
  • still an active pump ATPase on the basal/blood side (Na+/K+)
  • 2. Intercalated:
  • reabsorbs K+ - secretes H+, driven by ATPase

PRINCIPAL CELL

. .


  • Aldosterone (main mineralcorticoid) - GFR --> ACT (Glomerulosa secretes Aldosterone, Fasciculata secretes Cortisol, Reticulosa secretes sex hormones)
  • Aldosterone Largely determines urinary Na+ content, thereby regulating ECF volume
  • Secretion controlled by: (in order of most to least important)
  • (1) Angiotensin II
  • (2) K+
  • (3) ACTH
  • Atrial Naturietic peptide
  • ANP also contributes to Na+ excretion and ECF volume regulation
  • Responsive in low pressure range
  • Released by atrial stretch to cause:
  • – vasodilatation (including renal)
  • – increase GFR
  • – decrease aldosterone release (ie, reduced Na+/water retention)

INTERCALATED CELL

  • FLUID COMPOSITION:
  • Determined by volume state, acidosis and [K+]


  • Ion reabsorption:
  • H+/K+ ATPase (apical/luminal side)* --> Passive conductance K+ AND Na+(IN) + K+ Active pump ATPase (interstitial fluid/basal side)



**unusual to have an ATPase on luminal side
question5: COLLECTING DUCT. ROLE, MECHANISM, FLUID COMPOSITION? WHY PRODUCE A STRONGLY HYPERTONIC ENVIRONMENT IN THE MEDULLA?
contents5:
Collecting Duct

  • MAIN ROLE:
  • Final regulation of H2O excretion, and thereby urine concentration
  • MECHANISM:
  • CD normally impermeable to all, but rendered permeable to H2O by insertion of aquaporins into luminal membrane
  • FLUID COMPOSITION:
  • Osmolarity: 60-1,200 mOsm/L
  • Regulated by ADH - release controlled by hypothalamic osmoreceptors


Aquaporins

  • Family of water channels discovered in early 1990’s
  • Trans-membrane proteins with narrow, hour-glass shape and charged walls allowing water only to pass
  • Without them H2O moves slowly by osmosis only
  • 8+ sub-types identified:
  • Aquaporin 1
  • Site : PCT/Desc. LoH Basal membrane
  • Nature : Constant presence. Continuous H2O reabsorption
  • Aquaporin 2:
  • Site : CD luminal membrane
  • Nature: Insertion in response to ADH, Variable H20 reabsorption
  • Aquaporin 3:
  • Site : CD basal membrane
  • Nature: Constant presence. Continuous H20 reabsorption
  • Aquaporin 4:
  • Site : CD basal membrane
  • Nature: Constant presence. Continuous H20 reabsorption


ADH/vasopressin - largely determines ECF osmolarity - inserted of Aq-2 on luminal membrane

  • Small polypeptide released from posterior pituitary
  • Release primarily controlled by hypothalamic osmoreceptors
  • 3 types of receptors – all G-protein:
  • V1a
  • Site : Peripheral circulation
  • Role: Vasoconstriction
  • V2
  • Site: Renal collecting duct + Endothelium (& V1a)
  • Role : Aquaporin-2 insertion, Clotting factor release
  • V3 (V1b)
  • Site CNS
  • Role ACTH release


Why produce a strongly hypertonic environment in the medulla?

For highly efficient H2O reabsorption in the collecting duct (see later)
